Crate root for `ctx-scan`, a standalone tool that walks an arbitrary directory (no git dependency) and maintains a `.context/` mirror tree of LLM-generated summaries, keyed by content hash rather than git history.

The file itself is just module wiring and a doc comment — no logic. It re-exports five submodules: `cli` (argument parsing/dispatch via `cli::dispatch`), `error`, `hash` (content-hash-based change detection — the mechanism `--check`/`--update` rely on to avoid unnecessary model calls), `readme`, `runner` (the three programmatic entry points: `runner::scan_run`, `runner::check_run`, `runner::update_run`), and `walker` (directory traversal).

Key architectural fact not obvious from the module list: prompt files are read at runtime from a configurable directory (default `prompts/`, relative to process cwd) — this is intentionally decoupled from the directory tree being scanned, so prompts aren't expected to live alongside or inside the target tree. Anyone changing how prompts are located or defaulted should look at `cli`/`runner` since that resolution isn't in this file.

`--check` must remain a no-model-call, hash-only comparison; `--update` should only regenerate entries whose hash changed. This invariant lives across `hash` and `runner`, not enforced here, but this file's doc comment is the canonical statement of that contract — keep it in sync if the behavior changes.